Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Crisis
"Thirteen Days" ("Dreizehn Tage"), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas across many countries.
Everyone should watch this film, not only because it deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events—particularly regarding controversies surrounding a U.S. national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy summoned his closest advisors to the White House.
Airplane photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons station in Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and the decisions that could not be made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during those days.
Recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a panel discussion to discuss the film as well as the crisis it addresses.
Participants of this round included, among others: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a professor of political science at Harvard, who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
In addition, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was also present.
Although the cinematic treatment of the subject was criticized in several aspects, the participants in the discussion could agree that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressures that President Kennedy faced in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Consultants must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is exclusively the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be identified that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; furthermore, communication channels must remain open.
Driving an adversary into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow for understanding of the adversary's situation could prove to be disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, additional allies, and the opinion of the world had supported him.
· A certain amount of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into taking action.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors were meticulously examined and weighed was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a temporal leeway for deliberation even exist today in light of the currently existing mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the much-criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade that Kennedy imposed on Cuba was mainly intended to send a signal to Premier Khrushchev about Kennedy's intentions, and was not meant as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted more calmly?
After all, the USA had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Chruschtschew's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy showed concern regarding the consequences that the deployment of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have for Berlin.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
"In the end, 'the Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban crisis,' claimed historian Ernest May."
“Soon it will be too late,” was a widely spread argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the missiles— as they assumed — were en route to Cuba by sea.
A US force of about 180,000 troops was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a rapid bombardment that would have been on a larger scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "It took me thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that nuclear weapons were already present on Cuba: 162 warheads, of which 90 were strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information on the occasion of a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If yes, what have you recommended?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I was aware of it."
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
"I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and—on a much larger scale—his comrade Che Guevara were willing to let Cuba burn, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion would thus have resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government did not have sufficient knowledge of the facts (a situation that often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion would "undoubtedly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack against the USA.
Chruschtschow's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: airplanes of the U-2 type flying over Cuban airspace were shot down despite the explicit instructions to the contrary given by the chairman.
A difficult question that did not arise during this debate at Harvard is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself during the crisis by more rational behavior, but rather someone of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
Today's discussions about a limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible but quite realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the internet where essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis and current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
